EU Commission proposes new court in dispute over TTIP
To defuse the dispute over the planned transatlantic free trade agreement TTIP, the EU Commission has proposed a comprehensive reform of the current arbitration system.
The controversial private arbitration institutions for disputes between corporations and states are to be replaced by a more transparent system that is much more similar to traditional courts in terms of its functioning.
"We want to set up a system that citizens trust," said EU Commissioner Cecilia Malmström at the presentation.
The Swede plans to introduce the proposal as a European negotiating position in the free trade talks with the United States.
The German government announced support.
TTIP aims to create the largest free trade zone in the world with 800 million people.
The plans for the reform of the current arbitration procedures provide for the EU states and the USA to jointly select independent judges for a new investment court.
They should come in equal parts from the EU, the USA and third countries.
A second instance is also planned for the first time.
It would allow appeals against judgments.
So far, those involved in the proceedings have agreed among themselves on arbitrators, and there was no possibility of appeal against their judgments.
In the discussion over the past few months, it has become clear that citizens do not trust the old ISDS system in terms of fairness and justice, commented Malmström.
According to her own statements, she wants to work towards an international investment court in the long term.
Disputes between Chinese companies and EU countries could then be clarified there, for example.
The investor-state arbitration procedures (ISDS) demanded by large corporations in particular are considered to be one of the main reasons for the great resistance to TTIP in Europe.
The traditional courts of arbitration have been criticized by opponents as a kind of parallel justice system that companies can use to claim damages from taxpayers, undermine national laws or enforce lowering of consumer and environmental standards.
In initial statements, anti-TTIP organizations such as Campact described the EU Commission's proposals as inadequate.
The main criticism was that they should not apply to the already negotiated free trade agreement with Canada (Ceta).
The German Economics Secretary Matthias Machnig (SPD), on the other hand, described the plans as great progress.
In the reform, the Commission is taking into account key points that Federal Economics Minister Sigmar Gabriel worked out with other EU trade ministers in the spring.
The old system of private arbitration courts is off the table.
The French government also welcomed Malmström's plans.
The European business association BusinessEurope warned against restricting the legal options for business through too many new rules.
Small and medium-sized companies in particular could be disadvantaged as a result, it said.
It was still unclear on Wednesday when talks on the TTIP (Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership) free trade agreement could be concluded.
Negotiations have been going on since mid-2013.
However, the issue of investor protection has not yet been discussed with the USA.
A framework for the agreement was originally supposed to be in place by the end of this year.
This date is no longer considered tenable.
