One of them had also been charged with abuse of office.
He was legally acquitted of this charge in May.
The current trial has been adjourned.
According to senior public prosecutor Robert Riffel, the preliminary investigation revealed that between 2006 and 2011 the accused used funds from club accounts, which they were allowed to use in their functions, for private purposes.
He estimates the damage at around 400,000 euros.
The sports officials are also charged with financial crimes.
This fact was ruled out by the chair of the jury panel, judge Michaela Sanin.
It will be negotiated at a later date.
Regarding the rejection of infidelity, the defense argued that the association had never suffered a financial disadvantage.
The sports officials only charged expense allowances and led the sports club, for which they worked from 1982 to 2011 and in which they had invested a lot of time and money, out of debt - the liabilities in 2001 were around 600,000 schillings (approx. 44,000 euros) .
"At that time we were faced with the situation: should we continue the club or should we close it?" said one of the accused, a day job as a large-scale auditor for the tax office.
Together with his colleague and co-accused, he then decided to take on this task.
With all the risks.
"We advanced money and put our life insurance at the bank as security," he said at the hearing.
It was agreed with the association: You can freely manage the money, only no debts may be incurred.
Furthermore, the payment of the expense allowances retrospectively to 1991 was decided - with corresponding financial success.
Therefore, part of the expense allowances were only paid out years later, namely from 2003, when there was a plus in the account.
That's why flat-rate and not detailed debits appeared, explained the former chairman of the processes.
The two defendants managed the accounts and savings books together, said the second defendant.
The judge asked why the payments had not been disclosed to the association in detail.
The association was not interested in the details of financial management, only being debt-free was important, so the answer.
When investigations into abuse of office began against one official in 2011, an amount of EUR 120,000 was transferred to the association's account.
Those were reserves, the defendants explained.
This securities account was in the name of the second accused and, according to his statement, was not known to the association.
