He also wants to discuss the topic with his counterparts from the G7 countries, who are also meeting with industry representatives at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid switch to digital radio.
A test track is currently being built on Autobahn 9 in Bavaria to test new technology.
So that the driver "is not burdened with any additional liability risks", the federal government wants to "review the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt it to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometers per hour.
The federal government also wants to work for a change to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
In automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, and the driver is increasingly becoming a passenger.
The technology is primarily based on sensors and cameras that record the environment and process the data in a matter of seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economics, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are "not to be expected until well after 2020".
The authors of the study estimate the added value in the area of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions in Germany to be around 8.4 billion euros in 2025.
"The digital networking of cars can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD traffic politician Sören Bartol.
However, the question of liability in the event of accidents and the security of the drivers' personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans are still skeptical about self-driving cars - much more so than the French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the testing organization Dekra presented on Wednesday at the AA comes to the conclusion that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomously driving cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent do not expect it for 20 years So, 31 percent don't believe in it at all.
In France, 21 percent of those surveyed expect autonomous cars by 2025, in the USA 33 percent.
In any case, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to relinquishing control throughout the journey on all roads.
At least 15 percent could imagine that on the freeway in flowing traffic, and 45 percent in traffic jams.
A good one in four would under no circumstances let the car take control.
