Gaultier feels too old to be an enfant terrible
It is a mixture of a very large fashion show and a wax figure horror chamber: the designer Jean Paul Gaultier (63) presented an exhibition about his work in Munich on Wednesday.
The highlights: mannequins that look shockingly human thanks to video projections.
They wear the spectacular creations of the French designer, who became a big star of the fashion scene with Madonna's stage outfits, among other things - and with the fact that he put men in skirts.
"I can no longer say that I am the enfant terrible of haute couture because I have white hair."
"It used to be bleached, now it's real," said Gaultier.
For the visitors of the exhibition "From The Sidewalk To The Catwalk" (from the sidewalk to the catwalk), which can be seen from September 18th in the Kunsthalle of the Hypo-Kulturstiftung, it is fortunate that the fashion designer has changed his initially negative attitude has changed to a show about himself.
He was actually against it, because: "For me, an exhibition sounded a bit like death," he said.
When you die, you go to the museum.
The impressive collection had previously made stops in Montreal, Canada, and in Paris.
"It's about so much more than just pretty clothes," said Kunsthalle director Roger Diederen.
It's about tolerance, acceptance and the vision of an open society.
The exhibits give an insight into the work of the man, who can hardly be overseen, who wrote fashion history without ever having completed an apprenticeship.
The show is not structured chronologically, but it is an excellently choreographed total work of art that required a great deal of effort: a stylist was hired to do the hair for the dolls, for example.
According to curator Thierry-Maxime Loriot, the makers carted 14 tons of material to Munich.
Shortly before the start of the Oktoberfest there was a special treat: a lederhosen outfit with a corset.
Heidi meets Madonna.
Gaultier said he was always interested in strong women ("women are smarter than men") and in people who are a little different.
Gaultier's old teddy can also be seen in the exhibition.
It stands for the designer's first tentative steps towards fashion.
As a kid (he wasn't a good student and bad at football) he dressed his teddy bear in bras and dresses, Gaultier said.
His parents would not have allowed him to play with a doll.
He later taught himself how to design fashion.
He stole fashion magazines and looked at the designs of other designers, as Gaultier said in Munich.
Of course I bought it later.
He was unable to pay the models for his first fashion show.
They received nothing, but were allowed to keep their clothes.
Jewelery instead of curtains - Plauen lace as a fashion niche
The long embroidery machines in and around Plauen used to be about making meters.
The embroidered fabrics and lace were created in large quantities for customers who processed them into blankets and curtains, for example.
That alone no longer works today, explains Andreas Reinhardt, Managing Director of Modespitze Plauen.
Instead, fashion is important again.
In the early days of Plauen lace, fashion played a bigger role, but was then pushed out by the home textiles industry - and is now being rediscovered as a niche.
Reinhardt gives a few examples: lace in jewellery, in accessories such as bags and in regional costumes.
In general, the so-called vintage fashion, which is based on past style epochs, forms an increasing potential for orders.
Anyone who does not serve a niche in the textile industry in Germany is no longer on the market.
With us, they already account for half of all orders.
Modespitze Plauen, along with nine other companies, is a member of the Plauen lace and embroidery industry association.
Only they are allowed to wear the protected label.
In the last 15 years, around 80 percent of sales have collapsed.
Private specialist shops and wholesalers are almost gone.
Our products hardly ever reach customers in this way.
The mass-produced goods are nowadays manufactured much more cheaply in Asia and sold almost exclusively via chains.
In addition, exports are weakening, currently to Russia and the USA.
Enough reasons for new ways.
The industry association also tries to score points with environmental awareness, as Cordula Bauer from Stickperle in Falkenstein explains: "Since this year we have had a seal of quality that shows that we produce in an ecologically and socially responsible manner".
Reinhardt adds: "This also applies to the materials used".
Graduate designer Ute Schmidt teaches at the Schneeberg branch of the West Saxon University of Applied Sciences in Zwickau - in the faculty for applied arts - and specializes in embroidery and lace.
In order to stand up to the competition from Asia, you have to find high-quality and innovative products.
That takes time and courage.
A tension is created between the freshest ideas of the designers and the companies, which above all have to think economically," says Schmidt.
Therefore, an existing design is often only slightly varied in order to keep a customer base.
A few years ago, textile designer Kati Reuter revived the historic snowball lace.
The machine embroiders small balls in some places.
The Plauen master goldsmith Bianca Hallebach-Krauße was inspired by this: "Before, I couldn't do anything with traditional Plauen lace".
Now she uses the snowball tip for her jewelry.
In a complex process, she embosses the pattern in silver.
"Many people in the region identify with the topic of Plauen lace - young and old," says Reuter.
She also delivers to the USA, Australia and Finland - mainly to customers whose ancestors lived in Plauen and the surrounding area and who want a souvenir.
I see my jewelery as a modern ambassador for Plauen lace.
