EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish and thus expect consumers to take a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organization Foodwatch, which has a corresponding working paper from the EU, sharply criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are passed on to pregnant women and small children with full force," explained Matthias Wolfschmidt from Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values for the neurotoxin for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as sharks or swordfish, are to be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "political economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily contaminated with mercury that around 50 percent of the catches cannot be sold based on the current limit values.
After doubling the limit values, only 14.5 percent would be unsaleable.
In return for this easing, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limit values for other fish from the current 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
However, Foodwatch described this as a "trick" because smaller non-predatory fish, such as carp, are usually so low in pollution that they already comply with the planned maximum values today.
The reduction in small fish is therefore "a perfidious diversion that only helps the economy," explained Wolfschmidt.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and accumulates in the food chain, particularly in predatory fish.
The federal government therefore warns that "even small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in unborn children".
However, the Federal Ministry for the Environment explains on its website with regard to the applicable maximum values that a "health hazard to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through the burning of coal.
According to a written statement from the Federal Environment Ministry to Annalena Baerbock, member of the Green Party in the Bundestag, German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury a year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish, for example in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and extensively exceeded", the "Spiegel" quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings about mercury in fish were among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU warning system RASFF.
Foodwatch is calling on consumers to protest against the EU's plans at: www.mercury-action.foodwatch.de
